Johnny Mack's has been there since before I moved to the Slope in 1996. It really hasn't changed much in terms of the menu, the food, or even some of the people. It has regulars at the bar. A big P.S. 107 contingent on Fridays for dinner. Ballgames on TV by the bar. Big corner windows open up in the warm weather with a tiny sidewalk dining area. Prices are reasonable. The apple and walnut salad with chicken is a go to for me. So is the burger, which is reliably good. Great fries and sweet potato fries. For dessert you have to have the chocolate mousse. Also reliably good. The beer is cold and there's Fat Tire on tap. There's a full service bar too, and friendly staff. It's the neighborhood joint every neighborhood needs for comfort food and a hangout spot with you neighborhood friends. So if you're in the neighborhood, stop on by.

We had high hopes for this place as it looks so nice from the outside.  We were somewhat disappointed.  The beer list needs some more creative options as most of the beers are large-scale brews like shock top and Bud.  The craft entries tended to be watered-down options like "session beers".  The wine situation is even worse.  The menu only listed generic categories rather than vintners.  The waitress had to go look in back to find out what wines they actually have.  My date finally decided wine was not a good idea and ordered a special flavored margarita, which proved to be from a mix and was un-drinkable.  They were nice about it and got her a simple mixed drink.  The fried chicken was fabulous, right in their strike zone.  My date had the Tuna steak special which was awful.  Cooked too much and no discernible spice or flavor treatment, just plain fish with sesame seeds.  In general this place needs some vision with both their food, beverage and decor.  We love to patronize the neighborhood places but probably won't go back here again unless I'm by myself looking for great fried chicken...which I'll have to consume with an ice water!
